Wash and dry all produce. Preheat oven to 425 degrees. Peel @sweet potatoes{4}, then cut into ½-inch cubes. Place in a #medium pot{} with enough water to cover by 1 inch. Bring to a boil and cook until easily pierced by a knife, about ~{15%minutes}.

Meanwhile, trim, then thinly slice @scallions{2}, keeping greens and whites separate. Drain sweet potatoes once finished, then return to #pot along with scallion whites. Mash with a #potato masher{} or fork until smooth. Stir in @milk{1/3%cup} (we sent more). Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

> TIP: Add more milk as needed to create a creamy consistency.

Heat a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{} in a #large pan{} over medium-high heat. Pat @sirloin steak{24%ounce} dry with a #paper towel{}. Season all over with @salt{}, @pepper{}, and @Italian seasoning{1%tablespoon}. Add to pan and cook until browned and crusty, about ~{2%minutes} per side. Transfer steak to a #baking sheet{}. Remove pan from heat.

Place @green beans{12%ounce} on baking sheet with steak and toss with a large drizzle of @vegetable oil{}. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}. Roast in oven until beans are tender but still slightly crisp and steak is cooked to desired doneness, ~{8-12%minutes}. Remove from oven and transfer steak to a #plate{} to rest.

While steak rests, add @butter{2%tablespoon} to pan used for steak and let melt. Add @flour{1%tablespoon} and stir vigorously until it loses its raw smell, ~{1-2%minutes}. Stir in @beef demi-glace{1}, @water{1%cup}, and any resting juices from plate with steak, scraping up any browned bits on bottom. Let come to a boil, then lower heat and let simmer until thick and gravy-like. Season with @salt{} and @pepper{}.

Slice steak against the grain. Divide sweet potatoes and green beans between plates. Lay steak on top of sweet potatoes, then drizzle with sauce. Garnish with scallion greens.